05068nam a22006495i 9780822381877DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19941994ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223818777 a10.1515/97808223818772doi  a(DE-B1597)553817  a(OCoLC)841913163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN849.C3bR7 1994 7aLIT0042902bisacsh1 aRodriguez, Iliana Yamileth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHouse/Garden/Nation :bSpace, Gender, and Ethnicity in Post-Colonial Latin American Literatures by Women /cIliana Yamileth Rodriguez; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tExcursus -- tIntroduction -- tPART I Gender/Genre/Nation/Ethnicity The Masculine -- t1 Transitions: Modernism/Modernity -- tPART II Nation/Ethnicity/Gender/Genre The Feminine -- t2 Teresa de la Parra: Hacienda/Nation-Quid Pro Quo -- t3 Dulce Maria Loynaz: Garden/Nation- Parva Domus: Magna Quies -- t4 Jean Rhys: Island/Nation-Hortus Conclusus -- t5 Simone Schwarz-Bart: Provision Grounds/Nation- Et in Arcadia Ego -- t6 Gioconda Belli: Urban House/Nation-Domi Nostre -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow ironic, the author thought on learning of the Sandinista's electoral defeat, that at its death the Revolutionary State left Woman, Violeta Chamorro, located at the center. The election signaled the end of one transition and the beginning of another, with Woman somewhere on the border between the neo-liberal and marxist projects. It is such transitions that Ileana Rodríguez takes up here, unraveling their weave of gender, ethnicity, and nation as it is revealed in literature written by women.In House/Garden/Nation the narratives of five Centro-Caribbean writers illustrate these times of transition: Dulce María Loynáz, from colonial rule to independence in Cuba; Jean Rhys, from colony to commonwealth in Dominica; Simone Schwarz-Bart, from slave to free labor in Guadeloupe; Gioconda Belli, from oligarchic capitalism to social democratic socialism in Nicaragua; and Teresa de la Parra, from independence to modernity in Venezuela. Focusing on the nation as garden, hacienda, or plantation, Rodríguez shows us these writers debating the predicament of women under nation formation from within the confines of marriage and home.In reading these post-colonial literatures by women facing the crisis of transition, this study highlights urgent questions of destitution, migration, exile, and inexperience, but also networks of value allotted to women: beauty, clothing, love. As a counterpoint on issues of legality, policy, and marriage, Rodriguez includes a chapter on male writers: José Eustacio Rivera, Omar Cabezas, and Romulo Gallegos. Her work presents a sobering picture of women at a crossroads, continually circumscribed by history and culture, writing their way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCaribbean literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCaribbean literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDecolonization in literature. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aFeminism and literaturezCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aState, The, in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh1 aCarr, Robert1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is pa